    "recap_headline": "Seton Hall University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "South Orange, N.J. \u2013\nMason Christopher\nearned the victory by tossing six scoreless innings and allowing just two hits as the Pirates took the rubber match of their weekend series against Brown, 3-1, on Sunday afternoon.\nHow it Happened\nChristopher got into a bit of trouble early before settling in on the mound, allowing a walk and single in the top of the first with one out. The lefty was able to bare down and set down the next two hitters with a strikeout and a line out to evade an early deficit. Christopher's offense would then spot him a lead in the second, as a well-executed double steal with runners at the corners allowed\nTy Acker\nto score from third.\nChristopher was stellar after being spotted the lead, allowing just one hit and three baserunners over the final four innings of his outing. That one hit came to lead off the fifth inning on a bunt single, but was quickly erased on a 6-4-3 double play started by\nTommy Manzo\nat short.\nThe Hall would tack on some insurance runs in the later innings.\nMagnus Krieger\n, making his season debut, brought home the second Seton Hall run in the sixth on an RBI single to left which scored\nGabe Cavazzoni\n. In the seventh, a sacrifice fly from\nAidan Sengenberger\nallowed\nAiden Dill\nto score and give Seton Hall a 3-0 advantage.\nBrown's bats were quiet all day, but the visitors mounted a threat in the eighth. After loading the bases against\nStephen Curry\n, a hit batsman brought home the Bears' first run and put the tying run into scoring position.\nRyan Reich\nwas called in from the bullpen and shut the potential rally down, striking out Christian Butera to strand the bases loaded. Reich would then strike out the side in the ninth to put a punctuation mark on the Pirate win.\nUp Next\nThe Hall continues its homestand on Tuesday at 4 p.m. when it welcomes Wagner for a midweek non-conference tilt."
  },
